    "## Abstract\n",
    "Legged locomotion is not governed only by where trajectories settle; it is also shaped by how perturbations are transiently redirected while gait is underway. That perspective makes non-normal dynamics especially relevant, because non-normal operators can transiently amplify and redistribute perturbations even when their long-term behavior is stable. Framed this way, stroke should not merely slow walking. It should also compress the set of transient dynamical mechanisms available to support rhythmic coordination, rapid error correction, and leg-to-leg coupling.\n",
    "\n",
    "This manuscript argues that delay-embedded linear models provide a natural bridge between observable gait kinematics and those transient mechanisms. In benchmark nonlinear systems, the central interpretation is that stronger non-normality emerges when the learned linear surrogate must simultaneously encode rotation, decay, and history dependence. In human walking, the same logic predicts that impairment should weaken both the non-normal structure of the learned operator and the depth of temporal history that remains dynamically useful.\n",
    "\n",
    "To make that argument explicit, the document now includes a self-contained Julia implementation of delay-embedded Hankel DMD applied directly to the human dataset. The final analysis extracts three complementary quantities from each trial: departure from normality, short-horizon transient gain, and a temporal-memory centroid describing how predictive weight is distributed across the delay line. The strongest new result is that low-functioning stroke gait exhibits a compressed temporal memory kernel and a weaker speed-dependent expansion of that kernel than young adult and high-functioning stroke walking. This reframes post-stroke locomotor impairment as a loss of dynamical reserve, not only a shift to a slower operating point.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Introduction\n",
    "Locomotion is often summarized in terms of periodicity, limit cycles, and asymptotic stability. Those descriptions are important, but they are incomplete for real biological movement. Walking must remain functional in the face of internal noise, imperfect coordination, and continuous perturbations from the environment. In that setting, what matters is not only whether a trajectory returns to a nominal gait, but also how it transiently moves through state space on the way back.\n",
    "\n",
    "Non-normal dynamics offer a concise way to formalize that distinction. A non-normal operator can transiently amplify specific perturbation directions even when all eigenvalues imply eventual decay. For locomotion, that means the same system can appear globally stable while still expressing strongly directional, short-lived amplifications that shape step-to-step coordination. Those transient pathways are likely to matter for legged behavior because gait is inherently phase-structured, multi-timescale, and history dependent.\n",
    "\n",
    "Stroke is an especially useful test case for this viewpoint. Clinical gait deficits are usually described through slower preferred speeds, asymmetry, or elevated variability. But those behavioral observations are also compatible with a deeper hypothesis: stroke narrows the transient dynamical repertoire available to the locomotor system. If so, impairment should appear not only as altered kinematic trajectories, but as a reduction in the non-normal and temporally distributed structure of learned dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "Delay embedding is a practical way to probe that hypothesis. By constructing a Hankel state from successive observations, delay-embedded DMD lets us ask how much of present locomotor prediction depends on very recent versus more distributed history. That additional temporal structure is precisely where we expect stroke-related loss of dynamical richness to appear. The final analysis below therefore focuses on an interpretable question: does stroke compress the temporal memory kernel encoded by Hankel DMD, and does that compression limit how walking dynamics change with speed?\n",
    "\n",
    "## Methods\n",
    "### Human Dataset and Trial Organization\n",
    "The human dataset used here is loaded directly from the supplied NumPy file at `/home/michael/Documents/Python/HAVOK/delase/data/all_human_data.npy`, with trial-level annotations from `/home/michael/Documents/Python/HAVOK/delase/data/all_human_data_metadata.csv`. The tensor has shape `(299, 1500, 6)`, corresponding to 299 walking trials, 1500 time points per trial, and 6 observed kinematic channels per time point.\n",
    "\n",
    "Metadata divide the dataset into 17 young-adult subjects (`YA`), 5 able-bodied adult subjects (`AB`), and 20 stroke subjects (`ST`). Stroke trials are additionally labeled as low-functioning (`LF`) or high-functioning (`HF`) in the provided metadata. In the analyses below, each trial is treated as an independent realization of a six-dimensional locomotor state, while group-level summaries are pooled by those metadata labels.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Self-Contained Delay-Embedded Hankel DMD in Julia\n",
    "Rather than depending on an external package implementation, the analysis below builds a compact Hankel DMD pipeline directly in Julia. Each trial is first z-scored channel-wise so that operator comparisons reflect dynamical organization rather than raw amplitude alone. A delay-embedded matrix is then formed by stacking successive observations into a Hankel state. Singular value decomposition defines a low-dimensional coordinate system, and least-squares regression identifies a reduced operator that advances that latent state by one sample.\n",
    "\n",
    "The key point is that this procedure gives two complementary views of the learned dynamics. The reduced operator captures short-horizon amplification and departure from normality in the dominant latent subspace. The reconstructed full delay operator tells us how strongly each lag contributes to predicting the present state. That second object is especially useful for stroke locomotion because it lets us quantify whether predictive structure remains distributed across many delays or collapses toward a shallower, more immediate kernel.\n",
    "\n",
    "The implementation below uses `15` delays and a reduced Hankel rank of `15`. This choice keeps the model compact enough to remain interpretable while still preserving multi-step temporal structure. If a different embedding depth is preferred, the analysis is parameterized so those values can be changed in one place."
   ]
