    "### Dynamical Quantities Extracted from the Hankel Operator\n",
    "Three quantities are emphasized in the final analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "First, departure from normality measures how strongly the reduced operator differs from a normal matrix. Here it is computed as `||A'A - AA'|| / ||A||^2`, so larger values indicate stronger directional transient structure in the latent Hankel dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "Second, short-horizon transient gain measures how much the reduced operator can amplify perturbations over the first several forward steps. Rather than asking only whether the operator is asymptotically stable, this quantity asks whether the model contains directions that can grow transiently before they decay.\n",
    "\n",
    "Third, and most importantly for the wrap-up analysis, the reconstructed full delay operator is used to quantify a temporal memory kernel. The first row block of that operator encodes how strongly the next predicted state depends on the present block and progressively older delays. Normalizing those block norms yields a distribution over lag depth. Its centroid provides an interpretable measure of effective memory depth in lag samples, while the long-lag fraction captures how much predictive weight remains at the tail of the delay line.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Results\n",
    "### Strength of Non-Normality in Learned Dynamics Track Non-Linearity and Relaxation Timescales in Simulated Systems (Stuart Landau Oscillator, Van der Pol Oscillator, Lorenz System)\n",
    "The simulated benchmark systems motivate the interpretation used throughout the rest of the manuscript. When a learned linear surrogate must simultaneously encode rotation, dissipation, and delayed state exchange, non-normality is expected to rise. In practical terms, stronger non-normal structure should appear when the underlying system contains separated timescales or curvature that cannot be captured by a single orthogonal mode family. That benchmark intuition matters here because locomotion also combines rhythmic progression, damping, and coordinated inter-leg exchange in a partially observed setting.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Human Stroke Survivors Exhibit Reduced Non-Normality in Dynamics of Leg Kinematics During Walking\n",
    "The compact Hankel DMD fits recover systematically smaller departures from normality in stroke walking than in young-adult walking. Under the present embedding, median departure from normality is highest in `YA`, intermediate in `AB`, and lowest in `HF` and `LF`. That ordering is important even though the absolute values are small: it indicates that stroke trials are learned as more weakly direction-selective operators, consistent with a reduction in the transient structure available for coordinating leg motion.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Non-Normality of Leg Kinematics Dynamics Correlates with Walking Speed in Stroke Survivors\n",
    "Under this compact parametrization, the speed dependence of departure from normality is present but modest compared with the stronger temporal-memory effects below. That pattern is informative in itself. It suggests that stroke does not simply erase all transient amplification mechanisms. Instead, impairment appears to alter how far into the recent past the locomotor system remains dynamically coupled. In other words, the most robust speed-sensitive signature is not just the magnitude of non-normality, but the temporal distribution of predictive weight across delays.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Resolvent Analysis Reveals Amplification of Perturbations in Leg Kinematics Dynamics During Walking\n",
    "The reduced Hankel operators retain short-horizon gains above one across all groups, indicating that transient amplification remains possible even when the learned dynamics are bounded over longer horizons. This matters because it separates two features of gait control that are often conflated: having a stable locomotor regime, and having a dynamically rich regime. Stroke does not abolish transient amplification outright. Rather, the analysis suggests that amplification becomes embedded in a shallower temporal kernel with less distributed history dependence.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Final Analysis: Hankel DMD Reveals a Compressed Temporal Memory Kernel in Stroke Gait\n",
    "The most informative quantity in the human dataset is the temporal memory kernel implied by the delay operator. Faster and less impaired walking is associated with predictive structure that remains distributed deeper into the delay line, whereas low-functioning stroke gait shifts that weight toward shallower history. That is a stronger mechanistic statement than saying stroke survivors walk more slowly. It suggests that the locomotor system is operating with a reduced temporal horizon for coordinating present motion with the recent past."
   ]
